name: Lacey Griff
department: I’m so excited to be living my childhood dream of being a teacher! I have taught both kindergarten and 1st grade, but 1st grade is my absolute favorite. In my spare time I like to read, play with my 2 sweet dogs, float the river, and spend time with my husband. My husband and I also LOVE fostering dogs from the Humane Society when we can. This is my 14th year of teaching. I have a BA degree in Elementary Education & a Master’s degree in Elementary Reading & Math. I also have my National Board Certification.

name: Maggie Manzi
department: Mrs. Manzi loves teaching middle school math! She previously taught in Lynnfield, MA and New Bedford, MA. Mrs. Manzi is a graduate of the College of the Holy Cross and American International College. In her spare time, she enjoys relaxing on the beach, reading and cheering on Boston sports teams.

name: Frank Ravelo
department: HS Math and Head Baseball Coach

name: Avery Bowman
department: Hi everyone! My name is Avery Bowman and I am so excited to be rejoining the Rocket community as a math teacher! I graduated from Person High School in 2018. I then attended Meredith College where I played NCAA Division III volleyball and graduated with a degree in mathematics. While at Meredith, I also took many education courses to work towards obtaining a middle school and high school teaching license. Throughout my college career, I was employed as a math tutor both privately and for the Learning Center at Meredith. I also spent time observing and working with various math teachers in Wake County. In my free time, I enjoy listening to podcasts, going to the beach, and spending time with my friends and family. I am really looking forward to meeting and working with all of my students and their families to make each school year great!

name: Michael Crabtree
department: I attended United Township High School where I graduated with honors and completed 5 years of math course when only 3 years was required. After high school, I attended Western Illinois University where I obtained my Bachelor’s Degree in Mathematics and Women’s Studies. While attending college I tutored math ranging from algebra up to calculus III, then later tutored theory. I also taught algebra for 3 years where I administered and graded tests, helped students with questions, and addressed student concerns. After college I worked in retail as a manager where I trained several employees that moved to management positions, as well as managing profit and loss. I am excited to begin my career at Person High so I can help students succeed in math. I am passionate about teaching and will not give up on students, as well as be a friendly and helpful mentor.

name: Dr. Lawrence James
department: I am originally from the small town of Maiden located in western part of North Carolina.  I attended my first two years of high school at Maiden High School and then my last two years at Hargrave Military in Chatham VA.  During my high school years at Hargrave I was part of the band company playing the bagpipes, although as a student I barely made it through graduation.   After high school I enlisted in the United States Marine Corps and was stationed with the 2nd Marine Division at Camp Lejeune after boot camp at Parris Island.  My next duty station was 1st Marine Air Wing in Iwakuni, Japan where I remained for three years.  It was during that time that I realized I had a brain and had located it.  I decided that when my time was up in the Marine Corps I would go to college.  When I mustered out of the Marine Corps I started college at the University of North Carolina Asheville and then transferred to Wake Forest University.  My grades from high school were so poor that I was given one semester on probation.  If I did not achieve 2.0 or above that semester I would be asked to leave the university.  I did achieve above 2.0 and continued on to get a B.A. and M.S. in physics.  My first physics course I had to withdrawal because I did not have the mathematical preparation. To correct that deficiency I took a remedial math the following semester in order to catch up.  This course and the instructor helped to give me the confidence to continue my studies in physics. After finishing my M.S. at Wake Forest I went to North Carolina State University to work on my doctorate in physics.  I completed it in 1989 and went to work at Troxler Electronic Laboratories located in Research Triangle Park doing research and development for 7 years.  I separated from Troxler in order to help found a company InstroTek where in 2000 I became the Vice President of Research.  There I developed or helped to develop and obtain patents on many of the products InstroTek makes for the road building industry.  I retired in the year 2021 and began my second career teaching math at Person High School, something I felt called to do for the past decade or so. On June 19th of 2021 I married Heather Kennedy Mobley and we currently live in Timberlake, NC. After a significant layoff, and with Heather's encouragement, have resumed playing and practicing the bagpipes.

name: Jesse Mattos
department: Mrs. Mattos is a Roxboro native.  From an early age, she knew that she wanted to be a teacher, and for the past 16 years, she has served in a variety of educational roles, from Gen Ed Science & Math, to Math Interventionist, to EC Coordinator, and she is currently serving as an EC Inclusion and Resource Teacher.  This is her second year at Person High School, and she is honored to work with this wonderful team.  Mrs. Mattos has 3 beautiful step-daughters (Jailyn 21, Morgan 20, and Mallory 18), 2 very energetic sons (Hawk 8 & Blaze 7), and the sweetest German Shepard fur baby (Jasmine 1) .  Outside of school, you will find Mrs. Mattos taking care of her home and family.  She is an avid gardener, and loves being in nature, and enjoys staying active and keeping up with her boys.

name: Katherine Rice
department: Ms. Rice received her Bachelors in Secondary Education with an emphasis in Advanced Mathematics from Concordia University in Portland, Oregon and her Masters in Mathematics Education from NC State. She has taught every level of math from Math 1 support courses through AP Calculus BC, though her most extensive experience is in teaching Math 3. This is Ms. Rice's 14th year teaching. Ms. Rice teaches using a flipped classroom and collaborative groups. She believes that all students are capable of learning math at high levels and is deliberate to communicate clear expectations and make herself approachable so that all of her students will have the opportunity to comprehend what can often feel like a difficult subject. Ms. Rice's pandemic hobby was starting a houseplant collection and learning how to grow Alocasias from corms. She has three cats named Casanova, Don Juan, and Rico Suave and loves to read in her spare time.

name: Sanders, Sheila
department: Ms. Sanders is working on her second year as a MTSS-math interventionist at PHS. She attended and received her BA for Secondary Math Education at UNC at Wilmington. She taught in Wayne county for one year out of college, but has spent the rest of her teaching career at Person High School for a total of 24 years teaching Math. She has taught Algebra 1 and Algebra 2, Honors and Regular, but has taught Math 1 for the last 6 years. She is a member of Red Mountain Baptist Church in Rougemont, NC, where she helps with the youth group and many other activities. She loves teaching and helping youth become the best that they can be. She believes all children can learn and thrive if you push them and show them that you care for them. Once she has a child in her class or circle of classes, she considers them her children. She has high expectations for all of her students in and out of class. She wants them to reach the dreams that they have for their future. She loves and feels proud to see her former students thriving in all that they do: school, work, military, sports, family and so on. She enjoys keeping up with them after graduation.

name: Vonda Weaver
department: Ms. Weaver was born and raised in western NC and moved to the area to attend the University of NC at Chapel Hill. As an educator for more than 30 years, she has taught all age groups from birth to young adults in a variety of educational settings from private school to prison in four different counties.  This year marks her 21st year as a Person County Schools teacher.  For 15 years, Ms. Weaver taught math and science at Northern Middle School.  This is her sixth year as an EC teacher at PHS. Ms. Weaver’s greatest joy is spending time with her two children, Justin and Julia, and their cat, Steven Tyler.  Ms. Weaver enjoys reading, spending time outdoors, and cooking.

name: Whitman, Jennifer
department: My name is Jenn Whitman and I gladly serve PHS students and their families as a school counselor.  I reside in Person County with my three sons, Cameron, Cooper, and Cohen. Together, we enjoy being outside, listening to music, sitting by campfires, watching movies, traveling, and relaxing.  In my free time, I try to make time for fitness, hiking, running, biking, basically anything that gives me the chance to breathe fresh air.  I also enjoy reading and watching documentaries to relax/wind down. As a native of Person County and PHS alumni, I take pride in building and growing students to help them realize their potential and reach their goals in life (#InPerson&Beyond). In support of students, I hold a Master's Degree in School Counseling and teaching certifications in Middle and Secondary Mathematics, and Exceptional Children. I also have a Bachelor of Science in Business Administration and Marketing from Appalachian State University. Throughout my career, I've served in various roles through Person County Schools as a middle and high school math teacher, an Exceptional Children's teacher, and EC Lead.  Each role has provided me with experiences that I now use to support PHS students more holistically.  As an advocate for students, I encourage us all to work together as parents/guardians, teachers, administration, and staff to ensure students are receiving the support they need to guide them through their high school years. Please do not hesitate to contact me with any questions or concerns. I look forward to working with you all and getting to know your students throughout the school year!

name: Shelby Williams
department: I have worked in Person County Schools for 22 Years. I am the Online Coordinator /Facilitator for NCVPS (North Carolina Virtual Public School) NCSSM (North Carolina School Science & Math) and Credit Recovery Edgenuity. As a teacher, I feel that I can positively influence a child’s way of thinking or doing. Dreams lead to big ideas—which can lead to innovations and changes for the future.

name: Julie Holt
department: Hello Harmony Grove Community!My name is Julie Holt and I beginning my 4th year as the Math Instructional Coach at Harmony Grove Elementary School. Prior to this position, I spent 15 years as an educator within the classroom: five years at Stapleton Elementary as a fourth and fifth grade math, science, and social studies teacher as well as ten years teaching special education and upper elementary in Iowa. I am passionate in helping both educators and students receive the support they need to be successful.I have a constant love of learning, with a Bachelor’s degree in Elementary and Special Education with minors in liberal arts and math and a Master’s degree in Reading Education. I am currently studying for my Masters in Educational Leadership. I also love reading, the beach, and camping.

name: Claire Lowe
department: Dear Students and Families,Every child deserves the opportunity to learn and reach for his/her dreams. This is what I learned from my favorite poet, Langston Hughes, and it is the philosophy of our classroom. My name is Claire Lowe. I have been very lucky to have taught fourth and third grade at Harmony Grove since 1999. Previously I taught at Coast Academy School in Mombasa, Kenya. I love to travel and explore the world.When I teach math, I try to make it meaningful to students.  I believe all students can excel in math if they focus on understanding the concepts, not memorizing formulas.  Problem solving is a big part of fourth grade.  Students learn to apply the mathematical skills they already know to new situations.  Through reading, it is possible to travel far away, hear stories of people just like you and nothing like you, find new ideas, and learn new things.  Reading is an integral part of fourth grade.  If you wanted to improve as a soccer player or as a piano player, you would need to practice.  The same is true of reading, so students should read daily.  Writing is an important form of relaying ideas and self-expression.  Children write in response to reading, essays, fiction, and personal narratives. We explore six IB “Units of Inquiry” throughout the school year with the themes: Who We Are, Where We Are in Place and Time, How We Express Ourselves, Sharing the Planet, How the World Works, and How We Organize Ourselves.  In each unit we ask questions and make connections through reading, writing, math, science, and social studies to construct our understanding of the unit’s central idea.  We use the inquiry method to discuss primary source photographs, analyze maps, research, and create projects. Sincerely,Ms. Lowe

name: Peggy Olegario
department: My name is Mrs. Peggy Olegário and this is my 30th year teaching. I started in Framingham in 1992!  I am a very caring and open-minded person and I love teaching! I am principled and I always try to do the right thing while balancing my home and school life. I have two children, Maggie and Miguel, as well as a Shorkie (dog) named Mia. I currently live in Milford and I lived in Minas Gerais, Brazil for 8 years. After living in Brazil for 8 years, I became a good communicator in both English and Portuguese. In March of 2015, I returned from Brazil for a position as the substitute teacher in the third grade bilingual class and it was an amazing experience. My favorite subjects to teach are Math and Writing.  Some of my favorite books to read aloud are The Magical Yet, The Good Egg, The Bad Seed, and The Cool Cookie.  Stop into Room 205 and say “hi!”

name: Eleni Cordero
department: Ms. Eleni M. Cordero was born and raised in York County. Growing up with strong Greek and Puerto Rican roots, Ms. Cordero values family, culture and diversity. Ms. Cordero graduated from Millersville University with a Bachelor’s of Science in Elementary Education K-6. Teaching in several urban schools in York and Harrisburg Ms. Cordero furthered her education at Cabrini University earning her Masters in Educational Leadership with a K-12 Principal Certification. After 7 years of teaching middle-school math, Ms. Cordero served 1 year as an assistant middle school principal at Marshall Math Science Academy and 3 years as an Associate Principal at the Harrisburg High School John Harris Campus. A lifetime learner, Ms. Cordero is currently in the process of completing her Doctoral Program through Cabrini University in Organizational Development and Change. Ms. Cordero strives to do what is best for the students and the staff that she serves and hopes to bring positive and long lasting change to the Steelton-Highspire School District.
